Online Shoppers Dataset

Introduction to our Modeling

The “Online Shoppers Purchasing Intention Dataset” was found from the UCI archive and Kaggle, which was itself collected from Bahcesehir University in Istanbul, and gathered by the Inveon Information Technologies Consultancy and Trade in Istanbul. There are 12330 Observations, with 18 variables. We treated 17 of those columns as possible covariates in our models, and the remaining variable Revenue, was our response in all models. Our models were addressing whether the customer spent or not (represented by Revenue as a 1 and 0 respectively) based on the 17 features. These 17 features had a variety of available information, some from Google Analytics, and some from the website details/recorded cookies, which included the pages that the customer visited, how long they stayed on each page, their demographics, general page/website details, the website traffic at the time, and day/type of day when visited.

A big point of interest in our dataset was the unbalanced nature of our response variable. The greater majority (84.5%) of the consumers did not spend after their website visit, compared to a measly 15.5% who did. While this is easily explainable in the real world as a majority of website visitors can be expected to be e-window shopping rather than looking to make a purchase, this did increase the difficulty of the problem. We had to determine the best metric to use to determine our best model, and also look to the different ways to tackle the dataset so as to not under represent the information that predicts a possible buyer compared to a e-window shopper. In the end, given that both specificity and sensitivity would be innately imbalanced due to the revenue split, we decided to give up on accuracy as the metric for the model, and instead use AUC as the best metric going forward.

Finally, we decided to split our project into three possible models. We used Logistic Regression, Classification Trees, and K-Nearest Neighbors classification as the techniques to predict our response.

Smart Questions

Our Research Topic/Question: What variables are strong predictors of the likelihood that a consumer will generate revenue on an e-commerce site? Can we build a convincing model to determine the likelihood of that revenue generation?

Specific: We will be measuring the probability/likelihood of an online consumer to spend on the e-commerce site based on their attributes.

Measurable: Our label or dependent variable will be Revenue with classification models, which will be measured by if they spend on the website before exiting, or if they don’t. Since our dataset is only taken from one unnamed e-commerce site, there could be unaccounted-for bias if we take the population that we’re measuring to be the whole of e-commerce visits. Likewise, this dataset was taken over a single year, so at certain points, there is unaccounted variation by seasonality or holidays where shoppers would purchase more or less. Still, the features in the dataset look to lessen this impact by adding in Month, Weekend, and SpecialDay variables.

Achievable: Despite there being 12330 observations, the computing power needed to generate a model and do exploratory data analysis is achievable, and with three people working in the allotted time frame, the dataset is more than manageable. Of course, the more computationally-expensive models, like the regression tree, may need to be limited in depth and possibilities in order to fit within our time frame.

Relevant: Our dataset is relevant with e-commerce shopping being so popular with consumers. Nowadays, e-commerce companies heavily invest in AB testing, and the data/models provided from this project could give more insight into the direction that these companies would like to proceed in, in order to maximize their gains/appropriate metric.

Time-oriented: We will perform quick exploratory data analysis the first half to gain a better understanding of the new dataset we have chosen, and then for the second half, build models for prediction.

#Logistic Models

Initial Cleaning

In our initial .csv file, the data was already very clean and properly formatted for R to process. There were no NAs in the dataset, and no ommissions were made in the end. The only necessary bits of cleaning were to ensure that the variables were in the right data type to be inputted into the models.

We observed some very obvious correlation between things like the number of administrative pages visited and the amount of time each visitor spent on administrative pages, which is expected just like informational/informational_duration and productedRelated/productRelated_Duration.

The highest correlation with our response is the PageValues, which had a .49 correlation with Revenue. Again, this higher correlation makes sense because the PageValues feature is an average value/metric of the page visited before the user completed a transaction.

Other than that, the Bounce and Exit Rates both have a negative correlation with the likelihood of generating revenue, while users that visited productRelated pages seems to more likely generate revenue over users that visited admin or informational pages.

Below, we continue with a t-test to see if the PageValues covariate average value differs for those who spent on the website, and those who did not.

online_shopper_bought <- online_shoppers[which(online_shoppers$Revenue==TRUE),]
online_shopper_not <- online_shoppers[which(online_shoppers$Revenue==FALSE),]
t.test(online_shopper_bought$PageValues, online_shopper_not$PageValues, conf.level = .95)

Initial Logistic Regression

Here is the initial logistic regression using the correlation plot to select features. Generally, the covariates with the highest correlations with the response were selected, without including both pairs of the covariates that have high correlation with each other. For example, while ProductRelated and Product_Duration could both be predictors of Revenue, they have high correlation with each other, and Product_Duration is not included

This model looks to be a good model already. The coefficients are all statistically significant aside from the Informational pages, and the AIC is 7675.8. The AUC is .8883, which is higher than 0.8, which is evidence that the predictors are doing well in classifying the dataset.

Logistic Regression with the Full Model and K-NN cross validation.

For the full model, we used Cross Validation with our dataset with K=10 Folds to navigate around overfitting and possible variance in creating testing/training data. Our full model has both a higher accuracy, at .8878, AUC, at .9, AIC, at 7215, and McFadden score, at .334, than our initial model. This points to the fact that there is more information in our covariates that our models can utilize, without overfitting in the testing data.

set.seed(123)
train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
ShopModelCV <- train(Revenue ~., data = online_shoppers, method = "glm", family = "binomial", trControl = train_control)
summary(ShopModelCV)
unloadPkg("caret")

Logistic Regression with the Reduced Model and K-NN cross validation.

Finally, let’s reduce the number of features in this model, particularly the less significant ones that might be causing overfitting. Starting from the null model, let’s add the strongest predictors and move in both directions to achieve the best AIC.

full = ShopModelCV
null = glm(Revenue ~ 1, family = "binomial")
step(null, scope = list(lower=null, upper=full), direction = "both", criterion = "AIC")

Now we have our reduced logistic model, which is glm(formula = Revenue ~ PageValues + Month + ExitRates + ProductRelated_Duration + TrafficType + VisitorType + ProductRelated, family = “binomial”)

Interpretation and Model Comparison

All of the models had generally high accuracies and AUCs, but I would choose the final model as it has the lowest AIC out of the three models. While the McFadden and AUC of the full model was slightly higher than that of the reduced model, as the complexity is much less with only 7 out of the possible 17 different features, the lower complexity and balance between underfitting and overfitting between the initial and full model has me leaning more towards the reduced model. Lastly, by sacrificing accuracy, it is possible to greatly increase the true positive rate, though it will increase the false positive rate a bit. Again, so long as the AUC is good and the ROC curve is smooth throughout, the cutoff rate can be adjusted depending on the standards/metric of the e-commerce business at hand.

Inferential Statistics

We will perform Chi-Square test on all the last 6 categorical variables. For the variables with simulated p-value parameter False, the p-value is computed from the asymptotic chi-squared distribution of the test statistic. Otherwise, for variables without normal distribution p-value is calculated using Monte-Carlo simulations.

os_contable = table(df_orig$Revenue, df_orig$OperatingSystems)
# os_contable
chisq.test(os_contable, simulate.p.value=T)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with simulated p-value (based on 2000
##  replicates)
## 
## data:  os_contable
## X-squared = 75, df = NA, p-value = 5e-04
br_contable = table(df_orig$Revenue, df_orig$Browser)
# br_contable
chisq.test(br_contable, simulate.p.value=T)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with simulated p-value (based on 2000
##  replicates)
##

From above testing, all the variables except Region are statistically significant (p-value < 0.05). Region has p-value of 0.3 (>0.05) making it statistically insignificant. Hence we will omit the Region variable from our modeling.

Classification Tree Modeling and Hyperparameter Tuning

We will choose “maxdepth” parameter for our decision tree. For this we will be using original unbalanced dataset only.

loadPkg("rpart")
loadPkg("caret")
confusionMatrixResultDf = data.frame( Depth=numeric(0), Accuracy= numeric(0), Sensitivity=numeric(0), Specificity=numeric(0), Pos.Pred.Value=numeric(0), Neg.Pred.Value=numeric(0), Precision=numeric(0), Recall=numeric(0), F1=numeric(0), Prevalence=numeric(0), Detection.Rate=numeric(0), Detection.Prevalence=numeric(0), Balanced.Accuracy=numeric(0), row.names = NULL )

for (deep in 2:7) {
  tree_fit <- rpart(Revenue ~ . - Region, data=train, method="class", control = list(maxdepth = deep, cp=0.005))
   
  cm = confusionMatrix(predict(tree_fit, test, type = "class"), reference = test$Revenue, positive = "2")
  
  cmaccu = cm$overall['Accuracy']
  
  cmt = data.frame(Depth=deep, Accuracy = cmaccu, row.names = NULL)
  cmt = cbind( cmt, data.frame( t(cm$byClass)))
  confusionMatrixResultDf = rbind(confusionMatrixResultDf, cmt)

}

# Max Accuracy
online_pred_max <- knn(train = online_training, test = online_test, cl=online_trainLabels, k=15)
onlinePREDCross_max <- CrossTable(online_testLabels, online_pred, prop.chisq = FALSE)
# Selected Variable Model
online_pred_max_selected <- knn(train = online_training_selected, test = online_test_selected, cl=online_trainLabels_selected, k=25)
onlinePREDCross_max_selected <- CrossTable(online_testLabels_selected, online_pred_selected, prop.chisq = FALSE)
loadPkg("pROC")
# model with every variable
h <- roc(online_testLabels , as.integer(online_pred_max))
auc(h)
plot(h)

# model with specific variables
h_selected <- roc(online_testLabels_selected , as.integer(online_pred_max_selected))
auc(h_selected)
plot(h_selected)

Sadly, both models do not meet the cut off AUC metric of 0.8. We can see from the Confusion Matrix that when the models are at the optimal k value the total accuracy are in the high 80 percent levels. However, the issue we need to address is the specificity that is measured by taking the true negatives divided by the true negatives plus the false positives. For both models we built we can see that there are small specificity rates.

Concluding Remarks

In the end, we found that our models all had strengths and weaknesses in their approaches. Due to our use of cross-validation and proper training/testing splits, our results were consistent throughout multiple splits. Still, the problem mainly rested on balancing between specificity and sensitivity in our models, due to the unbalanced dataset. In that manner, our models were not all consistently producing a smooth ROC curve that maxmimized AUC, our metric of interest. Out of our final models, the logistic regression scored the highest AUC, with a very smooth curve, and the classification tree and K-NN models stood a bit below, and ran into the most problems with the unbalanced dataset. Going forward, more time-series information or even more observations would be helpful to balance the dataset and give more insight into the relationships between the covariates and Revenue.
